Earth and Planetary Science Letters

Volume 289, Issues 3–4, 31 January 2010, Pages 311-322

Deep pooling of low degree melts and volatile fluxes at the 85°E segment of the Gakkel Ridge: Evidence from olivine-hosted melt inclusions and glasses

Author links open overlay panel, , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.epsl.2009.11.018Get rights and content

Abstract

We present new analyses of volatile, major, and trace elements for a suite of glasses and melt inclusions from the 85°E segment of the ultra-slow spreading Gakkel Ridge. Samples from this segment include limu o pele and glass shards, proposed to result from CO2-driven explosive activity. The major element and volatile compositions of the melt inclusions are more variable and consistently more primitive than the glass data. CO2 contents in the melt inclusions extend to higher values (167–1596 ppm) than in the co-existing glasses (187–227 ppm), indicating that the melt inclusions were trapped at greater depths. These melt inclusions record the highest CO2 melt concentrations observed for a ridge environment. Based on a vapor saturation model, we estimate that the melt inclusions were trapped between seafloor depths (∼ 4 km) and ∼ 9 km below the seafloor. However, the glasses are all in equilibrium with their eruption depths, which is inconsistent with the rapid magma ascent rates expected for explosive activity. Melting conditions inferred from thermobarometry suggest relatively deep (25–40 km) and cold (1240°–1325 °C) melting conditions, consistent with a thermal structure calculated for the Gakkel Ridge. The water contents and trace element compositions of the melt inclusions and glasses are remarkably homogeneous; this is an unexpected result for ultra-slow spreading ridges, where magma mixing is generally thought to be less efficient based on the assumption that steady-state crustal magma chambers are absent in these environments. All melts can be described by a single liquid line of descent originating from a pooled melt composition that is consistent with the aggregate melt calculated from a geodynamic model for the Gakkel Ridge. These data suggest a model in which deep, low degree melts are efficiently pooled in the upper mantle (9–20 km depth), after which crystallization commences and continues during ascent and eruption. Based on our melting model and the assumption that CO2 is perfectly incompatible, we show that the highest CO2 concentrations of the melt inclusions (∼ 1600 ppm) are consistent with the calculated CO2 concentrations of primary undegassed melts. The highest measured CO2/Nb ratio (443) of Gakkel Ridge melt inclusions predicts a mantle CO2 content of 134 ppm and would result in a global ridge flux of 2.0 × 1012 mol CO2/yr.

1. Introduction

Melt inclusions provide a unique perspective on mid-ocean ridge (MOR) magmatic processes by preserving the compositions of melts generated at different depths within the upwelling mantle beneath mid-ocean ridges (Sobolev and Shimizu, 1993, Nielsen et al., 1995, Shimizu, 1998, Kamenetsky et al., 1998, Sours-Page et al., 2002, Maclennan et al., 2003a, Maclennan et al., 2003b, Laubier et al., 2007). MORB melt inclusions exhibit a great deal of compositional diversity, even within a single hand sample (Shimizu, 1998), and show significantly more variability on the segment-scale than do mid-ocean ridge glasses (e.g., Sours-Page et al., 1999). The homogeneity in glass compositions is thought to reflect melt aggregation processes, whereby melts are pooled and mixed prior to eruption at the seafloor. Rubin and Sinton (2007) showed that for global MORB the variance in mantle-derived chemical signatures generally decreases with decreasing Mg# and with increasing spreading rate. This argues that much of the homogenization occurs within melt-rich parts of the crust and thus will be more extreme at magmatically robust spreading centers. Melt inclusions provide a means to test these concepts by providing a window into melt compositions within deeper parts of the magmatic system before homogenization in crustal reservoirs.

Melt inclusions can also provide insight into volatile fluxes at ridges as they have the potential of recording geochemical relationships prior to degassing that are not preserved in basaltic glasses. Because CO2 and H2O become less soluble in silicate melts with decreasing pressure, an ascending magma will degas as it rises through the crust and mantle. Based on solubility-controlled vapor saturation models (e.g., Dixon et al., 1995), many studies have found that submarine glasses from mid-ocean ridges tend to record CO2 and H2O contents that are either in equilibrium or moderately super-saturated (≤ 1 kbar) with respect to their eruption depths (see summary in Saal et al., 2002). Super-saturation is typically ascribed to rapid ascent rates (le Roux et al., 2006), during which inefficient bubble growth and degassing prevent equilibrium from being attained (Bottinga and Javoy, 1990, Dixon & Stolper, 1995). However, even during rapid ascent, some degassing is likely to have occurred, thereby modifying the original volatile contents. Olivine-hosted melt inclusions may circumvent this problem by preserving primary undegassed volatile signatures to yield insight into deeper processes.

To date, only a few MORB melt inclusion studies have included volatile data (Sobolev, 1996, Sobolev and Chaussidon, 1996, Saal et al., 2002), with the latter being the only study in which both CO2 and H2O data are reported. Specifically, Saal et al. (2002) found that melt inclusions from the Siqueiros intra-transform spreading center were undersaturated with respect to their eruption depths, and thus, because the inclusions had never degassed, used these data to estimate volatile contents in the primitive upper mantle. To test whether undersaturation is typical of MORB melt inclusions and/or whether these samples are anomalous due to their transform origin, we investigate the volatile, major, and trace element compositions of melt inclusions and submarine glasses from 85°E on the ultra-slow spreading Gakkel Ridge (10 mm/yr full rate). Extant data (Dick et al., 2003, Michael et al., 2003) and models (Bown and White, 1994, Su et al., 1994, White et al., 2001, Montési & Behn, 2007) predict lower average extents of melting and a higher degree of compositional variability at the Gakkel Ridge as compared to faster spreading ridges (Rubin and Sinton, 2007, Rubin et al., 2009, Standish et al., 2008). In this study, we show that relatively low degree melts are recorded in both the glasses and the melt inclusions (maximum extent of melting ≤ 10%), but are remarkably homogeneous and can be described by a liquid line of descent originating from a single pooled melt. The pooled melt composition is consistent with the aggregate melt calculated from the melting model of Kinzler & Grove, 1992a, Kinzler & Grove, 1992b, Kinzler & Grove, 1993 and a thermal model for the Gakkel Ridge. Melt inclusions record volatile compositions that indicate pressures of entrapment equivalent to depths up to ∼ 9 km below seafloor and are overall less degassed and less fractionated than the glasses. These data are consistent with a model in which deep melts are efficiently pooled in the upper mantle near the top of the melting column, and then begin to crystallize and degas during ascent to the seafloor.

2. Geologic background and sample details

The Gakkel Ridge, spanning ∼ 1800 km across the Eastern Arctic Basin, is the ultra-slow end-member in the global ridge system (Fig. 1). Full spreading rates along the Gakkel Ridge are ∼ 6–14 mm/yr, more than an order of magnitude slower than the fast spreading East Pacific Rise (EPR). Three tectonic provinces have been identified along the Gakkel Ridge (Michael et al., 2003, Dick et al., 2003): (1) a magmatically robust western volcanic zone (WVZ), (2) a 300-km-long sparsely magmatic zone (SMZ), with abundant mantle peridotite exposures, and (3) an eastern volcanic zone (EVZ) characterized by widely spaced volcanic centers. The samples analyzed in this study were acquired from the 85°E segment, which is one of the major volcanic centers in the EVZ.

Based on Sr, Nd and Pb isotopes, trace elements (Goldstein et al., 2008), and other geochemical characteristics such as Ba/TiO2 ratios (Michael et al., 2003), the SMZ is considered to be a compositional boundary between the EVZ and the WVZ. Samples from the WVZ show ‘southern hemisphere’ Dupal-like geochemical characteristics, attributed to a source containing subcontinental lithospheric mantle. By contrast, samples from the EVZ have geochemical affinities similar to typical northern hemisphere ridges (Goldstein et al., 2008). Mg#s from the WVZ are distinctly lower than those from EVZ lavas (Michael et al., 2003), suggesting that that the EVZ lavas have undergone lower degrees of fractional crystallization and are more representative of primitive melts.

The samples selected for this study are from the 85°E volcanic center within the EVZ (Fig. 1; Table S1), and based on the studies described above, should represent relatively unfractionated melts, typical of northern hemisphere ridges. The samples, collected in July and August, 2007 on the Arctic Gakkel Vents (AGAVE) expedition (Sohn et al., 2008), include fresh glassy lavas and volcaniclastic material. The volcaniclastic material is thought to be the product of explosive volcanism based on the physical features of the glass shards, including bubble wall fragments (limu o Pele) and the large aerial extent over which the deposits were mapped (> 50 km2) (Sohn et al., 2008). Similar volcaniclastic samples have been acquired from MORs in the past (e.g., Head & Wilson, 2003, Clague et al., 2009, Hékinian et al., 2000, Pineau et al., 2004), but never at such great depths, nor over such a large area. The Gakkel 85°E samples were collected from depths of 3904–4131 m (Table S1) where pressures exceed the critical point for steam formation, ruling out lava interaction with seawater as a fragmentation mechanism. CO2 is the only magmatic volatile that would exsolve in MORBs at such pressures, which led Sohn et al. (2008) to propose that the explosive activity observed at the Gakkel Ridge was the result of extremely high CO2 contents in the magma during eruption.

3. Analytical techniques and methods

We measured major elements, trace elements, and major volatile concentrations (H2O, CO2, F, S, and Cl) on 26 naturally glassy olivine-hosted melt inclusions, as well as 15 submarine glass samples (see Fig. 1 and Table S1 for sample locations). Seven of the glass samples represent glassy rinds of individual pillow lavas collected at different sites. To evaluate whether volatile compositions from the proposed explosive eruption differed from typical eruptions, we also analyzed volcaniclastic material including limu o Pele fragments (4 samples) as well as more massive blocky chips (4 samples). All melt inclusions selected for this study were extracted from olivines contained within volcaniclastic glass chips from two sites, 12-1 and 13-1 (Fig. 1). Olivine grains were handpicked from crushed and sieved volcaniclastic material. Olivines containing naturally glassy melt inclusions were mounted in epoxy and hand-polished to expose inclusions, which were generally 30–100 μm in diameter. These flattened olivines, along with the suite of submarine glasses were then cleaned, mounted in indium metal (volatile blanks are significantly lower for indium mounts than for epoxy) and polished for ion and electron probe analyses. Major elements were measured on the glasses, melt inclusions, and host olivines with a JEOL-JXA-733 probe at the MIT Electron Microprobe Facility using a 15 kV accelerating voltage, a 10 nA beam intensity, and a spot size of 1–10 μm. Counting times were 5 s for Na and 40 s for all other elements. Each olivine grain was measured 3 times, at variable distances from the melt inclusion to test for compositional zoning and diffusion (Table S2). Volatile concentrations were analyzed using WHOI's 1280 ion microprobe following procedures developed by Hauri et al. (2002). A rastered 15–20 μm spot was measured with a 1–2 nA Cs+ beam. Combined accuracy and precision is ∼ 10% (2σ). The detection limits for H2O and CO2 are on the order of 100 ppm and 8 ppm, respectively. Trace elements were measured using the Cameca 6f ion microprobe at the Carnegie Institution of Washington, following procedures described by le Roux et al. (2006), using a 14–16 nA beam of O− with a 15–20 μm spot and detection of positive secondary ions with a nominal acceleration voltage of 10 kV. Energy filtering was employed (−75 ± 25 eV) and the calibration checked using NBSSRM and MPI-DING glasses. Trace element detection limits were measured using Herasil glass, and are very low (∼ 50 ppb for Sr and Ba; ∼ 20 ppb for Hf and Rare Earth Elements (REEs); ∼ 5 ppb for Nb) with the exception of Rb (4 ppm in basalt glass due to FeSi isobars). Combined accuracy and precision is 7% (2σ). Analytical reproducibility on separate chips of the same glass is typically 2–3% (2σ).

All melt inclusion compositions were corrected for post-entrapment crystallization by iteratively adding olivine back to melt compositions such that the inclusions are in equilibrium with their host olivine, assuming a Fe–Mg KD [=(FeO/MgO)olivine/(FeO/MgO)melt inclusion) of 0.3 and a Fe3+/total FeO of 0.15 (see Danyushevsky et al., 2002, Shaw et al., 2008 for correction methodology). The amount of olivine added to the inclusions is typically less than 5% (see Table S3), but slightly higher in a few cases and up to 10% in one case (sample 13-1_8). Following Shaw et al. (2008), an additional correction was made to account for the formation of a shrinkage bubble (present in 3 melt inclusions), which forms due to the differential contraction between the melt and the host crystal during cooling. By measuring the relative size of the melt inclusion and the vapor bubble, and calculating their respective volumes, we can then calculate the number of moles of gas present in the bubble with the ideal gas equation (n = PV/RT (Clapeyron, 1834)). The vapor saturation pressure derived from CO2 and H2O contents of the inclusions (Dixon et al., 1995), combined with an assumed glass transition temperature of 700 °C can be used to calculate the mole fractions of CO2 and H2O in the vapor, which can then be added back to the mass of the inclusion. This correction results in an insignificant change in H2O contents (< 0.001 wt.%), but can change CO2 contents dramatically (by as much as a factor of ∼ 4 for melt inclusion 13-1_10). However, despite the seemingly large correction for CO2 concentrations, the maximum CO2 concentration of the bubble-corrected melt inclusions do not exceed the natural range found in the bubble-free melt inclusions. Uncorrected melt inclusion compositions, inclusion sizes, and bubble diameters are reported in Table S4.

4. Results

Corrected major element, trace element, and volatile compositions for Gakkel glasses and melt inclusions are reported in Table S3 (major elements and volatiles) and Table S5 (trace elements).

4.1. Major elements

The major element compositions of the Gakkel melt inclusions are more variable and consistently more primitive than the glass data (Fig. 2), indicating that the melt inclusions represent melts that are less fractionated than the host glasses and possibly trapped at greater depths prior to mixing. The Mg#s of the glasses range from 64.2 to 67.5, within the range described by Michael et al. (2003) for Gakkel EVZ lavas (65.7 ± 4.3). By contrast, the melt inclusions have significantly higher Mg#s ranging from 68.9 up to 71.9. The olivines hosting the melt inclusions also have high Mg#s (87.3–89.3), suggesting that they originated from a melt that has undergone minimal amounts of fractional crystallization. Further, the linear relationship between Al2O3 and MgO contents in the Gakkel melt inclusions (Fig. 2B) indicates that olivine is likely the only mineral phase that has crystallized.

Several studies have argued that some melt inclusions may record anomalous compositions due to dissolution–reaction–mixing (DRM) processes at the margins of magma chambers (e.g., Kamenetsky et al., 1998, Bédard et al., 2000, Danyushevsky et al., 2003, Danyushevsky et al., 2004). In this context, the slightly elevated Sr contents of the Gakkel melt inclusions (Fig. 3A; 203–219 ppm compared to 129 and 181 ppm for Mid-Atlantic Ridge N-MORB and T-MORB, respectively (Klein, 2003)) could be interpreted in terms of plagioclase assimilation. However, the melt inclusions do not display elevated CaO contents and/or Eu anomalies indicative of reaction with pyroxene or plagioclase, suggesting that DRM processes have not strongly influenced these samples. Furthermore, we note that the elevated Sr contents are also present within the glass data set, thus arguing against a melt inclusion-specific process.

The Na2O contents of the Gakkel melt inclusions and glasses show little variation over the range of MgO contents (8–11 wt.%) and are high compared to N-MORB and the global melt inclusion dataset (Fig. 2D). The mean Na2O concentrations of glasses (3.23 wt.%) and melt inclusions (3.18 wt.%) are higher than the range found at “normal” ridge segments (2.77 ± 0.35 wt.%) based on the PetDB compilation of Su and Langmuir (2003). Such high values indicate relatively low degrees of melting, as would be expected for an ultra-slow spreading ridge, where efficient conductive cooling should truncate the top of the melting column at greater depth compared to faster spreading ridges (Reid & Jackson, 1981, Niu and Hékinian, 1997, White et al., 2001, Dick et al., 2003, Montési & Behn, 2007, Standish et al., 2008).

As described in Section 2, the Gakkel samples were taken from the EVZ, a region characterized by typical northern hemisphere MORB source (Goldstein et al., 2008), as opposed to the WVZ, which has more Dupal-like geochemical characteristics. Based on the K2O contents and K2O/TiO2, we infer that the source producing the 85°E Gakkel melts is more enriched than typical N-MORB and similar to a T-MORB source (Fig. 2G).

In summary, we find that compared to typical N-MORB (as compiled from the global ridge database), the major element chemistry of the Gakkel samples indicates that they were derived from a slightly enriched source that has undergone relatively low degrees of melting and minimal extents of fractional crystallization. Further, the melt inclusions have been influenced by differentiation processes to a lesser degree than the glasses, based on the higher Mg# of melt inclusions.

4.2. Volatile compositions

Volatile contents of glass samples show minimal variation indicating that the glasses are fairly homogeneous over the region sampled. Sulfur contents span a relatively narrow range from 883 to 940 ppm, and fluorine contents are essentially within error of each other, varying from 140–162 ppm. Chlorine contents of the glasses are mostly within the range of 26–43 ppm, with the exception of glasses from sample 12-1. Within the 12-1 samples, the 2 limu o Pele fragments, as well as the 2 glass chips have elevated chlorine contents (56–246 ppm) compared to the other glasses. These particular samples also have concomitantly elevated water contents, suggesting that these samples have likely been influenced by varying degrees of seawater contamination (e.g., Michael and Schilling, 1989, Kent et al., 1999) and thus are not deemed to be representative of true source compositions.

CO2 concentrations of the glasses vary from 187 to 227 ppm and water concentrations range from 0.21 to 0.26 wt.% (Fig. 4A), except for two samples with slightly higher water contents (0.28–0.32 wt.% H2O), which we attribute to interaction with seawater. Water contents of the glasses fall within the range observed at other ridge systems (e.g., 0.14–0.52 wt.% H2O at EPR (Jambon and Zimmermann, 1990, Michael, 1995), 0.15–0.5 wt.% H2O at MAR (Jambon and Zimmermann, 1990, Michael, 1995, Pineau et al., 2004) and 0.15–1.0 wt.% H2O at SWIR (Standish et al., 2008)). Based on the vapor saturation model of Dixon et al. (1995), all glasses are essentially in equilibrium with their eruption depth (∼ 3900–4100 m). None of the Gakkel glasses are super-saturated with respect to CO2 and water, as is the case for many submarine glasses. The volatile contents from the limu o Pele fragments are indistinguishable from the glass chips and thus we find no geochemical evidence to suggest that any of these melts ascended rapidly to the surface.

The concentrations of most volatile species measured in the Gakkel melt inclusions (n = 26) show a surprising lack of variability: water contents range from 0.24 to 0.28 wt.%, with one melt inclusion (13-1_5) having an extreme value of 0.48 wt.%; F concentrations vary from 137–166 ppm; S contents of melt inclusions show a slightly larger range than the glasses (707–990 ppm); Cl contents are relatively low (21–29 ppm) with the exception of 184 ppm in sample 13-1_5, which, again, likely reflects seawater-contamination. The calculated vapor saturation pressure of this particular sample (419 bar) suggests that entrapment was very close to seafloor depths, where opportunity for seawater interaction (and Cl contamination) would be greater (le Roux et al., 2006). The CO2 contents of melt inclusions show an exceptionally wide range of values, from 167 up to 1596 ppm. Using the Dixon et al. (1995) vapor saturation model we estimate that the melt inclusions were trapped at depths, starting as deep as ∼ 9 km below seafloor all the way up to seafloor depths (∼ 4000 m); in stark contrast with glasses, which are all in equilibrium with their eruption depths (Fig. 4A).

4.3. Trace elements

The trace element concentrations of the Gakkel glasses and melt inclusions fall within a narrow range, which is distinct from typical N-MORB compositions (Fig. 3). All samples are more enriched in light Rare Earth Elements (LREEs) and highly incompatible trace elements than N-MORB and seem to be consistent with T-MORB-like trace element patterns as defined for the Mid-Atlantic Ridge (Klein, 2003). Some of this apparent enrichment could be a consequence of the low extents of melting that characterize ultra-slow spreading environments (e.g., White et al., 2001, Standish et al., 2008). However, given the elevated K2O/TiO2 (see discussion above), it is likely that the source feeding the Gakkel melts is also slightly enriched. Perhaps the most surprising observation is that compared to our compilation of global MORB melt inclusions (Fig. 3B), the Gakkel melt inclusions are extremely homogeneous and essentially indistinguishable from the suite of Gakkel glasses. This is particularly remarkable given the expectation that slow- to ultra-slow spreading ridges should be characterized by enhanced geochemical diversity (Rubin and Sinton, 2007, Rubin et al., 2009).

5. Discussion

5.1. Implications for modification of melt inclusion compositions by diffusion

Several recent experimental and theoretical studies have argued that water in melt inclusions re-equilibrates rapidly (on the time-scale of hours to days) with the host magma via diffusion through the surrounding olivine crystal (Portnyagin et al., 2008, Gaetani & Hauri, 2008). If this occurs, then the water contents of the melt inclusions should be decoupled from the trace element concentrations, and simply reflect the water content of the last melt with which the inclusion equilibrated. However, melt inclusions and host glasses from subduction settings often show higher water contents in the melt inclusion phase, suggesting that the inclusions capture a deeper, less evolved water signature (Sobolev, 1996). Because melting systematics beneath ridges are simpler than at arcs and back-arcs, a quantitative comparison of melt inclusions and host glasses from mid-ocean ridges provides an ideal test for evaluating the influence of diffusive processes on melt inclusion compositions.

The Gakkel melt inclusions and host glasses show relatively uniform water contents (all uncontaminated data range from 0.21 to 0.28 wt.%) with no systematic pattern of higher contents in the melt inclusion phase (Fig. 4A). This similarity between the water contents of melt inclusions and their host glasses is observed at other MORB-related locations (Sobolev, 1996, Saal et al., 2002) and is consistent with the experimental data and theoretical models advocating rapid diffusion of water through olivine grains. However, it is also possible that these water contents represent true (but uniform) source compositions preserved at the time of entrapment.

To evaluate the possibility of diffusion-related mechanisms we consider the relationships between water and trace elements in the glasses and melt inclusions. Because trace element diffusivity in olivine is generally thought to be slow compared to that of water in olivine (e.g., Portnyagin et al., 2008), Cottrell and Kelley (2008) argued that diffusive equilibration of water between melt inclusions and their host magmas could be evaluated by comparing the relative variability of trace elements and water in melt inclusions. In situations where there is sufficient time for re-equilibration of water, but not trace element compositions, the melt inclusions should preserve greater variability in trace elements than in water. However, we find no evidence for higher variability in trace elements as compared to water contents in the Gakkel melt inclusions. For example, H2O and Ce — which are thought to have similar compatibilities, but different diffusivities (Michael, 1995, Dixon et al., 2002, Simons et al., 2002) — display no systematic differences in variability. Thus, the Gakkel samples show no clear evidence that diffusion has influenced the melt inclusion H2O contents. On the other hand, the observation that Mg and Fe (which diffuse faster than trace elements (Cottrell et al., 2002, Chakraborty, 1997) preserve variability (Fig. 2), argues that the trace elements in the Gakkel melt inclusions have not been significantly influenced by diffusion.

5.2. Pooled vs. incremental melts

Prior studies at mid-ocean ridges have found that melt inclusions typically record higher variability in trace elements and isotopic ratios than selvage glasses from the same samples (Nielsen et al., 1995, Shimizu, 1998, Kamenetsky et al., 1998, Sours-Page et al., 2002, Maclennan et al., 2003a, Maclennan et al., 2003b, Laubier et al., 2007). Within a given region or even within the same sample, light rare earth element (REE) patterns of melt inclusions can range from “ultra-depleted” (possibly indicative of melts derived from the top of the melting column and/or from a more depleted mantle) to light REE-enriched, the latter of which have been interpreted to result from deep melting of a garnet-bearing source (e.g., Sobolev and Shimizu, 1993, Gurenko and Chaussidon, 1995, Nielsen et al., 1995, Sobolev, 1996, Shimizu, 1998, Sours-Page et al., 2002). These compositions are thought to reflect melts produced and isolated at different depths throughout the melting column – possibly in a highly channelized melt transport system – and then preserved within melt inclusions (Spiegelman and Kelemen, 2003).

The homogeneity of the trace elements in the Gakkel inclusions suggests a pooled source composition. This interpretation is supported by the major element data (e.g., Al2O3, FeO, Na2O, and CaO), which show piece-wise linear correlations with MgO content, trending from the melt inclusions at high MgO to the host glasses at lower MgO contents (Fig. 2). These major element trends are consistent with fractional crystallization from a single starting composition. Because most models favor fractional (rather than batch) melting beneath mid-ocean ridges (e.g., Johnson et al., 1990), this implies that the Gakkel melt inclusions record melts that are efficiently pooled and homogenized prior to olivine crystallization.

To test the hypothesis that the Gakkel inclusions record a pooled melt composition, we constructed a geodynamic model for melting beneath the ultra-slow spreading Gakkel Ridge (Fig. 5A). Mantle flow and temperature structure were calculated in a 400-km wide × 250-km deep model domain using the COMSOL Multiphysics 3.5 finite element software. Mantle flow is driven by imposing a full spreading rate of 10 mm/yr at the surface of the model domain with stress free boundaries on the sides and bottom of the model space. The temperature at the surface is fixed to 0 °C and a mantle potential temperature of 1350 °C is extrapolated to the base of the model space assuming an adiabatic gradient of 0.5 °C/km. The mantle potential temperature was chosen based on the thermobarometry discussed in Section 5.3 and such that the calculated melt compositions fit the Gakkel data. In addition, this mantle temperature is within the range for global MORB defined by Herzberg et al. (2007).

We assume a visco-plastic temperature dependent rheology, which simulates brittle weakening within the lithosphere (Behn et al., 2007). Compared to a constant or temperature-dependent-only viscosity, the visco-plastic rheology promotes enhanced upwelling directly beneath the ridge axis, which has been shown to reproduce the thermal structure of oceanic transform faults (Behn et al., 2007) and melt focusing at intra-transform spreading centers (Gregg et al., 2009). Enhanced conductive cooling at the surface due to hydrothermal circulation is assumed at temperatures < 600 °C and depths < 6 km, using a Nusselt number of 4 (Phipps Morgan et al., 1987, Phipps Morgan & Chen, 1993, Gregg et al., 2009).

Melting is calculated from the resulting temperature structure based on the near-fractional, polybaric model of Kinzler & Grove, 1992a, Kinzler & Grove, 1992b, Kinzler & Grove, 1993 using the bulk depleted MORB mantle (DMM) composition of Workman and Hart (2005) (renormalized excluding Cr2O3, MnO, NiO, and P2O5) as the initial mantle composition. We assume a constant melt productivity of 1% melt per 1 kbar of ascent. At each melting step, 99% of the melt is removed and 1% is retained and ascends with the upwelling mantle. Following the procedures outlined in Gregg et al. (2009) we calculate melt fraction and incremental melt compositions as a function of pressure throughout the melting regime (Fig. 5A). The aggregated melt composition is then determined by pooling all incremental melts generated within the melting region and fractional crystallization trends are calculated using the approach of Yang et al. (1996). The Kinzler & Grove, 1992a, Kinzler & Grove, 1992b, Kinzler & Grove, 1993 melting model was derived for a nominally anhydrous mantle source. However, experimental charges likely had water contents up to those measured at the Gakkel (i.e., ∼ 0.2 wt.%; T. Grove, personal communication) and thus the predictions from this model should be relevant for this study.

Our calculations predict melting to begin at a depth of ∼ 60 km and reach a maximum melt fraction of ∼ 10% at ∼ 20 km below the ridge axis (Fig. 5A). The major element composition of the pooled melt corresponds closely to the melt inclusions with the highest MgO content and fractional crystallization trends calculated from the pooled melt closely follow the melt inclusion major element trajectories with decreasing MgO (Fig. 5B–E). By contrast, the incremental melt compositions predicted from the model are not consistent with the observed trends in SiO2, Na2O, and CaO versus MgO recorded in the Gakkel melt inclusions (Fig. 5). Thus, the Gakkel melt inclusions and host glasses appear to record a single liquid line of descent originating from an aggregate melt composition pooled over the entire melting region.

To evaluate whether the melt inclusion compositions represent primary undegassed melts, we used our melting model to calculate the CO2 content of the pooled melt. CO2 behavior during melting is nearly perfectly incompatible (Hauri et al., 2006, Hirschmann and Dasgupta, 2009); thus, by combining prior mantle source estimates for CO2 (36–160 ppm (Saal et al., 2002, Salters & Stracke, 2004, Workman and Hart, 2005, Cartigny et al., 2008)) with our melting model we can quantitatively predict CO2 concentrations of the pooled melt. Comparing these estimates to the melt inclusion compositions provides a test of whether the Gakkel melt inclusions are recording primary CO2 contents or whether even the highest CO2 concentrations have suffered considerable degassing. Assuming a mantle source composition of 50–150 ppm, and that CO2 behaves as a perfectly incompatible element, we calculate the pooled melt produced in the Gakkel melting regime to contain 900–2700 ppm CO2. Thus, the melt inclusions with the highest CO2 concentrations (∼ 1600 ppm) are within the calculated range for an undegassed pooled melt and correspond to a mantle source composition of ∼ 90 ppm CO2.

5.3. Melt generation, migration, and aggregation beneath the Gakkel Ridge

Based on the numerical modeling results and the major element, trace element, and volatile relationships recorded in the melt inclusions and glasses, we develop a conceptual model for melt generation, migration, and aggregation beneath the 85°E segment of the Gakkel Ridge. Consistent with previous numerical modeling studies at ultra-slow spreading ridges (e.g., Montési and Behn, 2007), we predict a cold upper mantle temperature structure beneath the Gakkel Ridge, which truncates the top of the melting column at ∼ 20 km depth (Fig. 5A). Using the thermobarometer of Lee et al. (2009), we find that the melting conditions preserved in the Gakkel samples are consistent with the thermal structure in the melting region calculated assuming a mantle potential temperature of 1350 °C (Fig. 6). This thermobarometer is based on the silica activity of the melt and is appropriate for samples that are in equilibrium with olivine and orthopyroxene and have crystallized only olivine — which is likely the case for the Gakkel samples based on the major and trace element relationships (Fig. 2, Fig. 5). The pressures and temperatures calculated from the major element compositions of the melt inclusions indicate that the pooled melts record relatively cold (1240°–1325 °C), deep (25–40 km) melting. These values fall within the range of P–T conditions predicted from our thermal model for the melt zone beneath the Gakkel Ridge (Figs. 5A and 6; Table S3). We show that the Gakkel data also record colder and deeper melting than melt inclusions from the FAMOUS area of the slow-spreading Mid-Atlantic Ridge (Laubier et al., 2007), as would be expected given the ultra-slow spreading rate of the Gakkel Ridge.

As discussed above, the major and trace element data combined with our numerical modeling results argue that the melts generated throughout this deep melting region are pooled before olivine crystallization. We speculate that this aggregation occurs in the upper mantle, between the top of the melting regime (∼ 20 km) and the maximum saturation depth (∼ 9 km) calculated from the H2O–CO2 systematics in the melt inclusions (Fig. 3A). In faster spreading environments, efficient pooling of melts is typically thought to occur within a shallow crustal magma chamber (e.g., Sinton and Detrick, 1992). If the aggregation process that homogenized the Gakkel melt inclusions also occurs within a magma chamber, the H2O–CO2 systematics indicate that such a chamber is located in the upper mantle. This is significantly deeper than the deepest seismically imaged magma chambers at slow – (Singh et al., 2006) and intermediate – (Collier and Sinha, 1990, Blacic et al., 2004, Van Ark et al., 2007) spreading ridges, which are situated in the mid- to lower- crust at depths of ∼ 3–5 km.

It is unclear whether a deep magma chamber beneath the 85°E segment of the Gakkel Ridge would be a steady-state or transient feature. Extreme focusing of melt into discrete magmatic centers separated by long amagmatic segments is characteristic of ultra-slow spreading environments (e.g., Dick et al., 2003, Jokat et al., 2003, Michael et al., 2003, Cannat et al., 2008). Magmatic centers at ultra-slow spreading ridges are thought to persist for millions of years — for example, the Narrowgate segment at 14.5°E on the Southwest Indian Ridge has been characterized by robust volcanic activity for > 8 Ma (Standish et al., 2008). Focusing of melt (and heat) over such long time periods could promote the formation of steady-state magma chambers in which melts could be efficiently mixed and homogenized. However, unlike the 85°E segment of the Gakkel Ridge, the Narrowgate segment displays heterogeneity in both major element compositions and incompatible element ratios that is not indicative of homogenization in a single magma chamber before fractional crystallization (Standish et al., 2008).

Assuming crystallization proceeds from a pooled melt within a deep magma chamber, we consider the melt extraction process as recorded by the Gakkel melt inclusions. The variation in MgO content at high CO2 concentrations (Fig. 4B) indicates that crystallization began at depths ≥9 km and continued to the seafloor. These observations are consistent with a discontinuous magmatic crust model for slow- and ultra-slow spreading ridges (Cannat, 1993, Cannat, 1996), where the cold axial thermal structure results in crystallization of rising melts within the upper mantle before reaching the crust (e.g., Elthon, 1987, Grove et al., 1992, Lizarralde et al., 2004, Kelemen et al., 2007). Whether ascent occurred during a single (potentially explosive) eruptive event, or through a slower upward migration process punctuated by arrest within sills (e.g., Cannat, 1993, Cannat, 1996, Korenaga and Kelemen, 1997), remains unclear. However, the lack of a systematic decrease in MgO with decreasing CO2 (i.e., pressure) implies that these melt inclusions do not record a single batch of melt crystallizing during ascent, but rather preserve distinct crystallization pathways.

5.4. CO2 flux from the Gakkel Ridge

Early estimates of the mantle's CO2 content (∼ 1000 ppm CO2) were based upon CO2 concentrations measured in the so-called “popping rock” (Javoy and Pineau, 1991), a highly vesicular MORB glass from 14°N on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, which has unfractionated noble gas ratios, suggesting minimal degassing (Javoy and Pineau, 1991, Moreira et al., 1998). Subsequent studies (Saal et al., 2002, Cartigny et al., 2008) derived mantle CO2 contents by coupling CO2/Nb ratios of melt inclusions and glasses (where CO2 and Nb are assumed to have similar partitioning behavior) with mean MORB Nb contents. Saal et al. (2002) measured CO2/Nb ratios of undersaturated olivine-hosted melt inclusions from the Siquieros intra-transform spreading center. Because vapor saturation models predict that these melts have never degassed, their relationships with trace elements should be preserved, and thus provide an estimate of 70 ppm CO2 in the MORB mantle source (Saal et al., 2002). More recently, Cartigny et al. (2008) measured CO2 contents and carbon isotopes of glasses from 14°N and 34°N on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and calculated significantly higher CO2/Nb ratios (∼ 530) than those reported by Saal et al. (2002) (∼ 239), which implies a CO2 content in the MORB source mantle of ∼ 160 ppm (assuming a Nb concentration of ∼ 0.3 in the MORB mantle (Hofmann, 1988, PetDB, 2009)). It is likely that the CO2/Nb ratio of the N-MORB source will differ from more enriched MORB sources, but the paucity of CO2/Nb data for undegassed samples makes such comparisons difficult at this stage.

The CO2/Nb ratios of the Gakkel glasses show little variability — ranging from 47 to 55; however the CO2/Nb ratio in the melt inclusions ranges from 44 to 443, with the upper limit approaching the modelled value of Cartigny et al. (2008). Moreover, the highest CO2/Nb ratio (443) is measured in the inclusion with the highest CO2 content and highest calculated pressure of entrapment, possibly most representative of the undegassed pooled melt composition. This value predicts a mantle CO2 content of 134 ppm, slightly higher than estimates from our melting model (90 ppm). The discrepancy between these two estimates likely reflects the uncertainty associated with the thermal/melting model, the assumption that Nb and CO2 have the same partitioning behavior, the variability in the Nb content of the MORB source mantle, and analytical errors. We cannot discount the possibility that some level of degassing has influenced the volatiles preserved in our melt inclusions — in which case the source CO2 content would be higher for both estimates.

Our measurements represent the first melt inclusions from a ridge environment with supersaturated CO2 values and thus can provide important new constraints on volatile fluxes from mid-ocean ridges. Using a similar approach to Cartigny et al. (2008), where CO2 source estimates are combined with a total oceanic crustal production rate of 21 km3/yr, a crustal density of 2.8 g/cm3, and a mean MORB Nb content of 3.31 ppm, we calculate a total ridge carbon flux of 1.2–2.0 × 1012 mol CO2/yr, using source estimates of 90 and 134 ppm, respectively. The upper limit is in good agreement with the estimate of Cartigny et al. (2008) (2.3 × 1012 mol CO2/yr), the lower limit of Dasgupta and Hirschmann (2006) (2.7 × 1012 mol CO2/yr), and with CO2 flux estimates based on He–C relationships (∼ 2.0 × 1012 mol CO2/yr based on combining He flux estimates (Craig et al., 1975, Farley et al., 1993) with CO2/3He measurements (Marty and Tolstikhin, 1998)). We note that this estimate for the CO2 flux from mid-ocean ridges is approximately equal to CO2 flux estimates proposed for arcs (1.5–3.1 × 1012 mol CO2/yr) (Sano and Williams, 1996, Marty and Tolstikhin, 1998, Hilton et al., 2002).

Applying the same approach as described by Saal et al. (2002), we use elements with similar partitioning behavior to the other volatile species measured in this study (H2O, F, S, and Cl) to derive source mantle compositions and volatile fluxes for the global ridge system (Table S6). The calculated global ridge fluxes of CO2 and S are similar to prior estimates, but the calculated H2O flux is ∼ 3 times lower (Marty and Tolstikhin, 1998, Cartigny et al., 2008, Hilton et al., 2002). Further, comparing these values to fluxes estimated for volcanic arcs (Hilton et al., 2002, Wallace, 2005), we find that Cl fluxes are nearly an order of magnitude lower than those of arcs, while the S flux is an order of magnitude larger at ridges and the H2O flux is approximately 5 times greater at ridges. Future studies are required to determine whether the Gakkel volatile flux estimates are representative of ridges worldwide.

5.5. Implications for eruption dynamics

The presence of widespread volcaniclastic material, interpreted as a pyroclastic deposit, on the seafloor across the 85°E segment of the Gakkel Ridge has led to the hypothesis that this material was the result of magmatically-driven explosive volcanism (Sohn et al., 2008). Because seafloor depths in this region exceed the critical point for seawater (∼ 3000 m), the explosive behavior was proposed to be the result of extremely high magmatic CO2 contents — Sohn et al. (2008) calculated that ∼ 13.5 wt.% CO2 would be required for magma fragmentation at 4000 m based on the model of Head and Wilson (2003). Our interpretation of melt aggregation in an upper mantle magma chamber could support a model for volatile driven explosivity, as it provides a location for CO2 to accumulate before eventual eruption. Based on the volume of the volcaniclastic deposit (∼ 5 × 10−4 km3 (Sohn et al., 2008)) and the CO2 flux for the Gakkel Ridge calculated above, it would take 1000–1700 yr to accumulate the amount of CO2 required for fragmentation at the seafloor (∼ 4000 m). This calculation assumes that all CO2 produced along a 10-km section of the ridge axis was collected in a single magma chamber. Assuming that melts at depths greater than 9 km are undegassed (see Section 5.2), the accumulated CO2 would be dissolved in the melt and an exsolved vapor phase would not form until the melt ascended to shallower depths. However, the Gakkel glasses show no evidence for super-saturation in CO2, thus it seems unlikely that these melts erupted directly from a deep magma chamber.

One model that could explain the seemingly contradictory observations of explosivity and the lack of super-saturation in the glasses is that the original CO2-rich melts migrated upward from a deep magma chamber and degassed in a shallower chamber near the seafloor. In this scenario, they could have produced a large CO2 gas “bubble” at the top of the shallow magma chamber, while retaining vapor saturation pressures in equilibrium with the seafloor. If sufficient magma was accumulated and degassed in this shallow chamber, while the CO2 bubble remained trapped, then it is possible that once the gas phase reached a critical volume, it could have triggered an explosive eruption. A drawback of this model is that a large amount of CO2 gas must be trapped in the uppermost crust, where permeability is high and confining stresses are low. Future work is required to determine whether the kinetics of CO2 bubble formation, the ascent rate between magma chambers, and the residence time in the shallow chamber are consistent with such a model.

6. Conclusions

Melt inclusions and submarine glasses from the 85°E segment of the ultra-slow spreading Gakkel Ridge record remarkably homogeneous major and trace element compositions, consistent with deep, low degree melts. Major element relationships indicate that the melt inclusions are systematically more primitive than the glasses, and can be described by a liquid line of descent originating from a single pooled melt composition. This composition is consistent with that predicted from the melting model of Kinzler & Grove, 1992a, Kinzler & Grove, 1992b, Kinzler & Grove, 1993 and a thermal model calculated for the Gakkel spreading rate of 10 mm/yr. Further, thermobarometry predicts deep (25–40 km), cold (1240°–1325 °C) melting, in agreement with the calculated temperature structure.

The volatile compositions of the Gakkel melt inclusions and glasses are relatively homogeneous with respect to H2O, F, S, and Cl. However, CO2 contents in the melt inclusions are significantly more variable than in the glasses, and indicate entrapment pressures up to ∼ 3 kbar (∼ 9 km below seafloor), while the CO2 contents of the glasses are in equilibrium with their eruption depths. The melt inclusions have the highest CO2 melt concentrations (up to ∼ 1600 ppm) reported for a ridge environment. Based on the CO2/Nb ratio of the highest CO2 bearing melt inclusion (CO2/Nb = 443) we calculate a MORB source mantle CO2 content 134 ppm, corresponding to a global ridge flux of 2.0 × 1012 mol CO2/yr (Table S6). This estimate agrees with CO2 flux estimates derived from both He–C systematics (Marty and Tolstikhin, 1998) and modelled CO2/Nb ratios (Cartigny et al., 2008).

The extremely homogeneous major and trace element compositions of the melt inclusions suggest the presence of a magma chamber or a melt reservoir in the upper mantle beneath the Gakkel Ridge at 85°E. Specifically, our data support a model in which deep melts generated beneath a thick thermal boundary layer are efficiently pooled at depths of 9–20 km. Based on the H2O–CO2 saturation pressures recorded in the melt inclusions, the aggregated melt begins crystallizing at depths ≥9 km, and continues up to the seafloor. Future work is required to determine whether deep magma chambers are common features to volcanic centers at ultra-slow spreading ridges.

  • High-C content and CO<inf>2</inf>/Ba ratio of the Earth's enriched upper mantle

    2023, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta
    Citation Excerpt :

    The Sr, Nd, and Pb isotopic compositions of the glasses from the Rano Rahi seamounts (Hall et al., 2006), Pukapuka ridges (Janney et al., 2000), SEPR axis (Mahoney et al., 1994) and off-axis lava field samples (Geshi et al., 2007) are also shown in Table S1. The chemical compositions of MORB glasses (Siqueiros transform fault, Saal et al., 2002; EPR, Mid-Atlantic Ridge (MAR), Southeast Indian Ridge (SEIR), and Gakkel Ridge, Michael and Graham, 2015; EPR, Shimizu et al., 2016) and melt inclusions (Siqueiros transform fault, Saal et al., 2002; Gakkel Ridge, Shaw et al., 2010; Juan de Fuca (JDF) Ridge (Axial Seamount), Helo et al., 2011; JDF Ridge, Wanless and Shaw, 2012; Gakkel Ridge, Wanless et al., 2014; MAR (Lucky Strike), Wanless et al., 2015; MAR, Le Voyer et al., 2017; Siqueiros & Garrett transform faults, Shimizu et al., 2019) for which CO2 contents are available from previous studies were compiled to place our new data in the context of previous data. Most of the Rano Rahi and Pukapuka samples are tholeiitic to alkalic basalts in major element composition with alkali contents (Na2O + K2O) and SiO2 ranging from 2 wt% to 5.5 wt% and 47 wt% to 53 wt% respectively (Fig. S3).

    One of the fundamental constraints on the carbon content in the Earth’s mantle comes from depleted mid-ocean ridge basalts (D-MORB) that experienced minimal CO degassing. The CO/Ba ratio of 120 ± 20 in these D-MORB have been used to estimate the CO content in more enriched MORB (e.g., N- and E-MORB) that have lost CO through degassing. However, it has been unclear as to how constant the CO/Ba ratio is in D-, N-, and E-MORB, which are known to derive from partial melting of a chemically and isotopically heterogeneous upper mantle. In this study, we constrained the CO/Ba ratio of the E-MORB mantle source in the Pacific by studying the compositions of MORB glass samples from the southern East Pacific Rise (on– and off-axial SEPR and Garrett transform fault) as well as volcanic glass samples from the Pukapuka ridges and Rano Rahi seamounts that extend to the west of the SEPR. Some of the submarine glasses from the Rano Rahi seamounts are D-MORB with highly depleted CO and incompatible trace element contents, but with isotopic composition pointing to a long-term enriched mantle source. These lavas were generated by re-melting of the residual Pacific E-MORB mantle source that had undergone a recent melting episode responsible for the Pukapuka ridge magmatism. Some Rano Rahi seamount lavas experienced limited CO degassing during eruption, and we consider that their most reliable pre-degassing CO/Ba ratio is the maximum value of 241 ± 30, measured in the most trace element depleted but isotopically enriched sample. While we show that this high CO/Ba ratio is in part due to fractionation during the earlier melting event that generated the Pukapuka ridges, the estimated initial CO/Ba ratio of the Pacific E-MORB mantle source is , still higher on average than that of the D-MORB mantle source (120 ± 20). We use this CO/Ba ratio for the Pacific E-MORB mantle source to provide an estimate of its CO content of ppm. We speculate that the high CO/Ba and C-enriched nature of the Pacific E-MORB mantle source could originate from either (1) recycling of oceanic lithosphere at subduction zones or (2) foundering of metasomatized continental lithospheric mantle into the convecting mantle.
